{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658805"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:55:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:55:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20824"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20824"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13699"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105402"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13699"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20824"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87829"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"1238"},{"type":"tags","id":"2171"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"11708"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32992"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38283"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105402"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic requesting bowel cancer screening. She is concerned because her mother was diagnosed with bowel cancer at age 62. She has no gastrointestinal symptoms. She has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has never had bowel cancer screening before.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination is unremarkable with no masses or tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate test to recommend?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Digital rectal examination","Faecal occult blood test","Colonoscopy","CT colonography","Flexible sigmoidoscopy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is at above average risk (Category 1 risk) for colorectal cancer based on having one first-degree relative diagnosed after age 62. Current guidelines recommend faecal occult blood testing as the initial screening test for individuals at average or slightly above average risk aged 45-74 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFaecal occult blood test\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate screening test in this scenario. It is non-invasive, cost-effective, and has been shown to reduce colorectal cancer mortality when used as part of a screening program. The test should be repeated every two years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E as an initial screening test should be reserved for individuals in higher risk categories, or known genetic syndromes. It is also used as a subsequent investigation for positive faecal occult blood tests.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexible sigmoidoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E examines only the distal colon and is not recommended as a primary screening tool in Australia. While it has been used in some screening programs internationally, the faecal occult blood test is preferred in the Australian healthcare system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT colonography\u003C/strong\u003E is typically reserved for patients who are unsuitable for colonoscopy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnnual digital rectal examination\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as a screening test for colorectal cancer as it can only detect lesions within reach of the examining finger and has not been shown to reduce mortality from colorectal cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Faecal occult blood testing is the recommended initial screening test for colorectal cancer in average-risk individuals aged 45-74 years.","Family history of one first-degree relative diagnosed with colorectal cancer at age 60 or older represents above average risk."],"references":["Choosing wisely [Internet]. [cited 2025 Mar 31]. Don\u2019t order colonoscopy as a screening test for bowel cancer in people at average or slightly above average risk. Use faecal occult blood screening instead. Available from: https://www.choosingwisely.org.au/recommendations/racgp6","Cancer Council Australia. Clinical practice guidelines for the prevention, early detection and management of colorectal cancer: Risk and screening based on family history. 2024. Available at: https://app.magicapp.org/#/guideline/jz5DdE"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87829"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20824"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87829"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-08T23:12:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-08T23:12:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13699"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105402"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id